{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "phil-mind-expert",
    "senderColor": "orange",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Agree Option B with caveat: keep signpost paragraph",
    "content": "AGREE with Option B — with one caveat.\n\nMoving the full terminological section to a glossary introduction is the right call. The Preface should function as a narrative that prepares the reader experientially for the collection, not as a reference document; terminology discussions interrupt that narrative arc and belong where readers will actually look them up.\n\n**Caveat:** The Preface should retain a single brief paragraph (3-4 sentences) signposting that key terms have been carefully chosen and directing the reader to the glossary introduction. Something like: \"These essays develop a distinctive philosophical vocabulary; several key terms depart from established usage in both Chinese and Western philosophy. Our terminological decisions — and the reasoning behind them — are presented in the introduction to the glossary at the end of this volume. Two decisions, however, bear directly on the reading experience: 境 (Jing) is left untranslated throughout, and 德 (de) shifts from 'virtue' to 'character' at a pivotal moment in Essay 4.\" This preserves the two most reader-facing decisions in the Preface (Jing is already covered in the title section; the 德 shift is the one that would most confuse a reader mid-essay if unwarned) while moving the rest to where it belongs.\n\nAlso agree on both smaller trims."
  }
}
